# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: netflow-sflow
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] There are multiple ways to acquire packets for deep packet inspection.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Using port mirroring (sometimes called Span Port) is a very common way, as well as physically inserting a network tap which duplicates and sends the data stream to an analyzer tool for inspection.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection (and filtering) enables advanced network management, user service, and security functions as well as Internet data mining, eavesdropping, and censorship.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Although DPI has been used for Internet management for many years, some advocates of net neutrality fear that the technique may be used anticompetitively or to reduce the openness of the Internet.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] DPI is used in a wide range of applications, at the “enterprise level” (according to corporations and larger institutions), telecommunications service providers, and governments.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] DPI technology has a long and technologically advanced history, starting in the 1990s, before the technology entered what is seen today as common, mainstream deployments.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Essential DPI functionality includes analysis of packet headers and protocol fields.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] For example, Wireshark offers essential DPI functionality through its numerous dissectors that display field names and content and, in some cases, offer interpretation of field values.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Some security solutions that offer DPI combine the functionality of an intrusion detection system (IDS) and an intrusion prevention system (IPS) with a traditional stateful firewall.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] This combination makes it possible to detect certain attacks that neither the IDS/IPS nor the stateful firewall can catch on their own.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Stateful firewalls, while able to see the beginning and end of a packet flow, cannot catch events on their own that would be out of bounds for a particular application.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] While IDSs are able to detect intrusions, they have very little capability in blocking such an attack.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] DPIs are used to prevent attacks from viruses and worms at wire speeds.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] More specifically, DPI can be effective against buffer overflow attacks, denial-of-service attacks (DoS), sophisticated intrusions, and a small percentage of worms that fit within a single packet.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] DPI-enabled devices have the ability to look at Layer 2 and beyond Layer 3 of the OSI model.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] In some cases, DPI can be invoked to look through Layer 2-7 of the OSI model.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] This includes headers and data protocol structures as well as the payload of the message.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] DPI functionality is invoked when a device looks or takes other action based on information beyond Layer 3 of the OSI model.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] DPI can identify and classify traffic based on a signature database that includes information extracted from the data part of a packet, allowing finer control than classification based only on header information.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] End points can utilize encryption and obfuscation techniques to evade DPI actions in many cases.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] A classified packet may be redirected, marked/tagged (see quality of service), blocked, rate limited, and of course, reported to a reporting agent in the network.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] In this way, HTTP errors of different classifications may be identified and forwarded for analysis.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Many DPI devices can identify packet flows (rather than packet-by-packet analysis), allowing control actions based on accumulated flow information.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Initially security at the enterprise level was just a perimeter discipline, with a dominant philosophy of keeping unauthorized users out, and shielding authorized users from the outside world.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The most frequently used tool for accomplishing this has been a stateful firewall.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] It can permit fine-grained control of access from the outside world to pre-defined destinations on the internal network, as well as permitting access back to other hosts only if a request to the outside world has been made previously.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Vulnerabilities exist at network layers, however, that are not visible to a stateful firewall.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Firewalls also do not distinguish between permitted and forbidden uses of legitimately-accessed applications.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] DPI enables IT administrators and security officials to set policies and enforce them at all layers, including the application and user layer to help combat those threats.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection is able to detect a few kinds of buffer overflow attacks.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] DPI may be used by enterprise for Data Leak Prevention (DLP).
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] When an e-mail user tries to send a protected file, the user may be given information on how to get the proper clearance to send the file.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] In addition to using DPI to secure their internal networks, Internet service providers (ISPs) also apply it on the public networks provided to customers.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Common uses of DPI by ISPs are lawful intercept, policy definition and enforcement, targeted advertising, quality of service, offering tiered services, and copyright enforcement.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Service providers are required by almost all governments worldwide to enable lawful intercept capabilities.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Decades ago in a legacy telephone environment, this was met by creating a traffic access point (TAP) using an intercepting proxy server that connects to the government's surveillance equipment.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The acquisition component of this functionality may be provided in many ways, including DPI, DPI-enabled products that are "LI or CALEA-compliant" can be used – when directed by a court order – to access a user's datastream.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] In some countries the ISPs are required to perform filtering, depending on the country's laws.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] DPI allows service providers to "readily know the packets of information you are receiving online—from e-mail, to websites, to sharing of music, video and software downloads".
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Because ISPs route the traffic of all of their customers, they are able to monitor web-browsing habits in a very detailed way allowing them to gain information about their customers' interests, which can be used by companies specializing in targeted advertising.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] At least 100,000 United States customers are tracked this way, and as many as 10% of U.S. customers have been tracked in this way.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Technology providers include NebuAd, Front Porch, and Phorm.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] ISPs monitoring their customers include Knology and Wide Open West.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] In addition, the United Kingdom ISP British Telecom has admitted testing solutions from Phorm without their customers' knowledge or consent.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Applications such as peer-to-peer (P2P) traffic present increasing problems for broadband service providers.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Typically, P2P traffic is used by applications that do file sharing.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] These may be any kind of files (i.e. documents, music, videos, or applications).
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Due to the frequently large size of media files being transferred, P2P drives increasing traffic loads, requiring additional network capacity.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Service providers say a minority of users generate large quantities of P2P traffic and degrade performance for the majority of broadband subscribers using applications such as e-mail or Web browsing which use less bandwidth.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Poor network performance increases customer dissatisfaction and leads to a decline in service revenues.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] DPI allows the operators to oversell their available bandwidth while ensuring equitable bandwidth distribution to all users by preventing network congestion.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Additionally, a higher priority can be allocated to a VoIP or video conferencing call which requires low latency versus web browsing which does not.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] This is the approach that service providers use to dynamically allocate bandwidth according to traffic that is passing through their networks.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Mobile and broadband service providers use DPI as a means to implement tiered service plans, to differentiate "walled garden" services from "value added", "all-you-can-eat" and "one-size-fits-all" data services.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] ISPs are sometimes requested by copyright owners or required by courts or official policy to help enforce copyrights.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] In 2006, one of Denmark's largest ISPs, Tele2, was given a court injunction and told it must block its customers from accessing The Pirate Bay, a launching point for BitTorrent.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Instead of prosecuting file sharers one at a time, the International Federation of the Phonographic Industry (IFPI) and the big four record labels EMI, Sony BMG, Universal Music, and Warner Music have sued ISPs such as Eircom for not doing enough about protecting their copyrights.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA), which aims to enforce movie copyrights, has taken the position with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) that network neutrality could hurt anti-piracy techniques such as deep packet inspection and other forms of filtering.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] In addition to using DPI for the security of their own networks, governments in North America, Europe, and Asia use DPI for various purposes such as surveillance and censorship.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The Chinese government uses deep packet inspection to monitor and censor network traffic and content that it claims is harmful to Chinese citizens or state interests.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] This material includes pornography, information on religion, and political dissent.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Chinese network ISPs use DPI to see if there is any sensitive keyword going through their network.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] China previously blocked all VoIP traffic in and out of their country but many available VoIP applications now function in China.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Voice traffic in Skype is unaffected, although text messages are subject to filtering, and messages containing sensitive material, such as curse-words, are simply not delivered, with no notification provided to either participant in the conversation.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] China also blocks visual media sites such as YouTube.com and various photography and blogging sites.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Since 2015, Egypt reportedly started to join the list which was constantly being denied by the Egyptian National Telecom Regulatory Authority (NTRA) officials.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] However, it came to news when the country decided to block the encrypted messaging app Signal as announced by the application's developer.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] In April 2017, all VoIP applications including FaceTime, Facebook Messenger, Viber, WhatsApp calls and Skype have been all blocked in the country.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] As of 2022, FaceTime, Facebook Messenger are unblocked.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The Indian ISP Jio, which is also the largest network operator in India has been known to employ sophisticated DPI techniques like SNI-based filtering to enforce censorship.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The Indonesian government via Telkom Indonesia, supported by Cisco Meraki DPI technology, perform country-wide surveillance by the way of deep packet inspection, and map it into SSN/NIK (Nomor Induk Kependudukan) of its citizens that registered to the state-owned ISP.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The purpose of deep packet inspection including filtering porn, hate speech, and reducing tension in West Papua.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Indonesian Government planned to scale up the surveillance to next level until 2030.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] According to unnamed experts cited in the article, the system "enables authorities to not only block communication but to monitor it to gather information about individuals, as well as alter it for disinformation purposes".
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The system was purchased by the Telecommunication Infrastructure Co., part of the Iranian government's telecom monopoly.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] According to the *Journal*, NSN "provided equipment to Iran last year under the internationally recognized concept of 'lawful intercept,' said Mr.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] That relates to intercepting data for the purposes of combating terrorism, child pornography, drug trafficking, and other criminal activities carried out online, a capability that most if not all telecom companies have, he said....
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] He said the company determined it was no longer part of its core business.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The NSN system followed on purchases by Iran from Secure Computing Corp. earlier in the decade.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Questions have been raised about the reporting reliability of the *Journal* report by David Isenberg, an independent Washington, D.C.–based analyst and Cato Institute Adjunct Scholar, specifically saying that Mr.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Roome is denying the quotes attributed to him and that he, Isenberg, also had similar complaints with one of the same *Journal* reporters in an earlier story.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] NSN has issued the following denial: NSN "has not provided any deep packet inspection, web censorship or Internet filtering capability to Iran".
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] A concurrent article in *The New York Times* stated the NSN sale had been covered in a "spate of news reports in April [2009], including *The Washington Times*," and reviewed censorship of the Internet and other media in the country, but did not mention DPI.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] According to Walid Al-Saqaf, the developer of the internet censorship circumventor Alkasir, Iran was using deep packet inspection in February 2012, bringing internet speeds in the entire country to a near standstill.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] This briefly eliminated access to tools such as Tor and Alkasir.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The incumbent Malaysian government, headed by Barisan Nasional, was said to be using DPI against a political opponent during the run-up to the 13th general elections held on 5 May 2013.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The purpose of DPI, in this instance, was to block and/or hinder access to selected websites, e.g.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Facebook accounts, blogs and news portals.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The Pakistan Telecommunication Authority (PTA) states that the DPI system has been installed to implement the Prevention of Electronic Crimes Act (PECA) 2016, particularly to filter and block blasphemous content and any material that is considered to be against the integrity or security of Pakistan.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Canadian firm Sandvine was contracted to provide and set up the equipment in Pakistan.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Federal Law No.139 enforces blocking websites on the Russian Internet blacklist using IP filtering, but does not force ISPs into analyzing the data part of packets.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Yet some ISPs still use different DPI solutions to implement blacklisting.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] For 2019, the governmental agency Roskomnadzor is planning a nationwide rollout of DPI after the pilot project in one of the country's regions, at an estimated cost of 20 billion roubles (US$300M).
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The city state reportedly employs deep packet inspection of Internet traffic.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] FCC adopts Internet CALEA requirements: The FCC, pursuant to its mandate from the U.S.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Congress, and in line with the policies of most countries worldwide, has required that all telecommunication providers, including Internet services, be capable of supporting the execution of a court order to provide real-time communication forensics of specified users.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] In 2006, the FCC adopted new Title 47, Subpart Z, rules requiring Internet Access Providers to meet these requirements.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] DPI was one of the platforms essential to meeting this requirement and has been deployed for this purpose throughout the U.S.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The National Security Agency (NSA), with cooperation from AT&T Inc., has used deep packet inspection to make internet traffic surveillance, sorting, and forwarding more intelligent.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The DPI is used to find which packets are carrying e-mail or a Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) telephone call.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Traffic associated with AT&T's Common Backbone was "split" between two fibers, dividing the signal so that 50 percent of the signal strength went to each output fiber.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] One of the output fibers was diverted to a secure room; the other carried communications on to AT&T's switching equipment.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The secure room contained Narus traffic analyzers and logic servers; Narus states that such devices are capable of real-time data collection (recording data for consideration) and capture at 10 gigabits per second.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Certain traffic was selected and sent over a dedicated line to a "central location" for analysis.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] According to an affidavit by expert witness J.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Narus's Semantic Traffic Analyzer software, which runs on IBM or Dell Linux servers using DPI, sorts through IP traffic at 10 Gbit/s to pick out specific messages based on a targeted e-mail address, IP address or, in the case of VoIP, telephone number.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Gonzales have asserted that they believe the president has the authority to order secret intercepts of telephone and e-mail exchanges between people inside the United States and their contacts abroad without obtaining a FISA warrant.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] The Defense Information Systems Agency has developed a sensor platform that uses deep packet inspection.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Vietnam launched its network security center and required ISPs to upgrade their hardware systems to use deep packet inspection to block Internet traffic.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection is considered by many to undermine the infrastructure of the internet.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] There is a greater emphasis being placed on deep packet inspection - this comes in light after the rejection of both the SOPA and PIPA bills.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Many current DPI methods are slow and costly, especially for high bandwidth applications.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] More efficient methods of DPI are being developed.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Specialized routers are now able to perform DPI; routers armed with a dictionary of programs will help identify the purposes behind the LAN and internet traffic they are routing.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] Cisco Systems is now on their second iteration of DPI enabled routers, with their announcement of the CISCO ISR G2 router.
[src:netflow-sflow/deep-packet-inspection] A comprehensive comparison of various network traffic classifiers, which depend on deep packet inspection (PACE, OpenDPI, 4 different configurations of L7-filter, NDPI, Libprotoident, and Cisco NBAR), is shown in the Independent Comparison of Popular DPI Tools for Traffic Classification.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] The IPFIX standards requirements were outlined in the original RFC 3917.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] Cisco NetFlow Version 9 was the basis for IPFIX.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] The basic specifications for IPFIX are documented in RFC 7011 through RFC 7015, and RFC 5103.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] A pool of **Metering Processes** collects data packets at one or more **Observation Points**, optionally filters them and aggregates information about these packets.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] An **Exporter** then gathers each of the Observation Points together into an **Observation Domain** and sends this information via the IPFIX protocol to a **Collector**.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] Exporters and Collectors are in a many-to-many relationship: One Exporter can send data to many Collectors and one Collector can receive data from many Exporters.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] Similar to the NetFlow Protocol, IPFIX considers a **flow** to be any number of packets observed in a specific timeslot and sharing a number of properties, e.g.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] "**same source, same destination, same protocol**".
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] Using IPFIX, devices like routers can inform a central monitoring station about their view of a potentially larger network.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] IPFIX is a **push protocol**, i.e. each sender will periodically send IPFIX messages to configured receivers without any interaction by the receiver.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] The actual makeup of data in IPFIX messages is to a great extent up to the sender.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] IPFIX introduces the makeup of these messages to the receiver with the help of special **Templates**.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] The sender is also free to use user-defined data types in its messages, so the protocol is freely extensible and can adapt to different scenarios.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] IPFIX prefers the Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP) as its transport layer protocol, but also allows the use of the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) or User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] As can be seen, the message contains the IPFIX header and two IPFIX Sets: One Template Set that introduces the build-up of the Data Set used, as well as one Data Set, which contains the actual data.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] When IPFIX is sent over a protocol which keeps a session state (TCP or SCTP), the Template Set need not be retransmitted since it is buffered in Collectors.
[src:netflow-sflow/ip-flow-information-export] Since the Template Set can change over time, it must be retransmitted if a new session state is established or if IPFIX is sent over UDP which is a session-less protocol.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Routers and switches that support NetFlow can collect IP traffic statistics on all interfaces where NetFlow is enabled, and later export those statistics as NetFlow records toward at least one NetFlow collector—typically a server that does the actual traffic analysis.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Note that the Egress interface, IP Nexthop or BGP Nexthops are not part of the key, and may not be accurate if the route changes before the expiration of the flow, or if load-balancing is done per-packet.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] This definition of flows is also used for IPv6, and a similar definition is used for MPLS and Ethernet flows.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Advanced NetFlow or IPFIX implementations like Cisco Flexible NetFlow allow user-defined flow keys.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] The router will output a flow record when it determines that the flow is finished.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] It does this by flow aging: when the router sees new traffic for an existing flow it resets the aging counter.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Also, TCP session termination in a TCP flow causes the router to expire the flow.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Routers can also be configured to output a flow record at a fixed interval even if the flow is still ongoing.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] NetFlow records are traditionally exported using User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and collected using a NetFlow collector.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] The IP address of the NetFlow collector and the destination UDP port must be configured on the sending router.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] A common value is UDP port 2055, but other values like 9555 or 9995, 9025, 9026 etc. can also be used.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] For efficiency reasons, the router traditionally does not keep track of flow records already exported, so if a NetFlow packet is dropped due to network congestion or packet corruption, all contained records are lost forever.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] The UDP protocol does not inform the router of the loss so it can send the packets again.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] This can be a real problem, especially with NetFlow v8 or v9 that can aggregate a lot of packets or flows into a single record.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] A single UDP packet loss can cause a huge impact on the statistics of some flows.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] That is why some modern implementations of NetFlow use the Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP) to export packets so as to provide some protection against packet loss, and make sure that NetFlow v9 templates are received before any related record is exported.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Note that TCP would not be suitable for NetFlow because a strict ordering of packets would cause excessive buffering and delays.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] The problem with SCTP is that it requires interaction between each NetFlow collector and each router exporting NetFlow.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] There may be performance limitations if a router has to deal with many NetFlow collectors, and a NetFlow collector has to deal with many routers, especially when some of them are unavailable due to failure or maintenance.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] SCTP may not be efficient if NetFlow must be exported toward several independent collectors, some of which may be test servers that can go down at any moment.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] UDP allows simple replication of NetFlow packets using Network taps or L2 or L3 Mirroring.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Simple stateless equipment can also filter or change the destination address of NetFlow UDP packets if necessary.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Since NetFlow export almost only use network backbone links, packet loss will often be negligible.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] If it happens, it will mostly be on the link between the network and the NetFlow collectors.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] A NetFlow record can contain a wide variety of information about the traffic in a given flow.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] For ICMP flows, the Source Port is zero, and the Destination Port number field codes ICMP message Type and Code (port = ICMP-Type * 256 + ICMP-Code) .
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] The source and destination Autonomous System (AS) number fields can report the destination AS (last AS of AS-Path) or the immediate neighbor AS (first AS of AS-Path) depending on the router configuration.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] But the AS number will be zero if the feature is not supported, the route is unknown or not announced by BGP, or the AS is the local AS.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] There is no explicit way to distinguish between these cases.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] By analyzing flow data, a picture of traffic flow and traffic volume in a network can be built.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] The NetFlow record format has evolved over time, hence the inclusion of version numbers.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Cisco maintains details of the different version numbers and the layout of the packets for each version.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] NetFlow is usually enabled on a per-interface basis to limit load on the router components involved in NetFlow, or to limit the amount of NetFlow records exported.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] NetFlow usually captures all packets received by an ingress IP interface, but some NetFlow implementations use IP filters to decide if a packet can be observed by NetFlow.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Some NetFlow implementations also allow the observation of packets on the egress IP interface, but this must be used with care: all flows from any ingress interface with NetFlow enabled to any interface with NetFlow enabled could be counted twice.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Standard NetFlow was designed to process all IP packets on an interface.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] But in some environments, e.g. on Internet backbones, that was too costly, due to the extra processing required for each packet, and large number of simultaneous flows.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] So Cisco introduced sampled NetFlow on Cisco 12000, and that is now used in all high-end routers that implement NetFlow.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Only one packet out of *n* is processed, where *n*, the sampling rate, is determined by the router configuration.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Some implementations have more complex methods to sample packets, like per-flow sampling on Cisco Catalysts.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] The sampling rate is often the same for all interfaces, but can be adjusted per interface for some routers.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] When Sampled NetFlow is used, the NetFlow records must be adjusted for the effect of sampling - traffic volumes, in particular, are now an estimate rather than the actual measured flow volume.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] NetFlow was initially implemented by Cisco, and described in an "informational" document that was not on the standards track: RFC 3954 – Cisco Systems NetFlow Services Export Version 9.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] The NetFlow protocol itself has been superseded by Internet Protocol Flow Information eXport (IPFIX).
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Based on the NetFlow Version 9 implementation, IPFIX is on the IETF standards track with RFC 5101 (obsoleted by RFC 7011), RFC 5102 (obsoleted by RFC 7012), etc. which were published in 2008.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Many vendors other than Cisco provide similar network flow monitoring technology.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] NetFlow may be a prevalent name in the area of flow monitoring, because of Cisco dominant market share in the networking industry.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Also flow-tools collection of software allows to process and manage NetFlow exports from Cisco and Juniper routers.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Introduced with the launch of the Cisco ASA 5580 products, NetFlow Security Event Logging utilizes NetFlow v9 fields and templates in order to efficiently deliver security telemetry in high performance environments.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] NetFlow Security Event Logging scales better than syslog while offering the same level of detail and granularity in logged events.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] NetFlow collection using standalone NetFlow probes is an alternative to flow collection from routers and switches.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] This approach can overcome some limitations of router-based NetFlow monitoring.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] The probes are transparently connected to the monitored link as a passive appliance using the TAP or SPAN port of the appliance.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Historically, NetFlow monitoring is easier to implement in a dedicated probe than in a router.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] The easiest way to address the above drawbacks is to use a packet capture appliance inline in front of the router and capture all of the NetFlow output from the router.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] This method allows for storage of large amount of NetFlow data (typically many years worth of data) and does not require reconfiguration of the network.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] NetFlow collection from dedicated probes is well suited for observation of critical links, whereas NetFlow on routers provides a Network-wide view of the traffic that can be used for capacity planning, accounting, performance monitoring, and security.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] NetFlow was originally a Cisco packet switching technology for Cisco routers, implemented in IOS 11.x around 1996.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] It was originally a software implementation for the Cisco 7000, 7200 and 7500, where it was thought as an improvement over the then current Cisco Fast Switching.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Netflow was invented by Darren Kerr and Barry Bruin from Cisco (U.S. patent # 6,243,667 ).
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] The idea was that the first packet of a flow would create a NetFlow switching record.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] This record would then be used for all later packets of the same flow, until the expiration of the flow.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] Only the first packet of a flow would require an investigation of the route table to find the most specific matching route.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] This is an expensive operation in software implementations, especially the old ones without Forwarding information base.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] The NetFlow switching record was actually some kind of route cache record, and old versions of IOS still refer to the NetFlow cache as **ip route-cache**.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] This technology was advantageous for local networks.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] This was especially true if some of the traffic had to be filtered by an ACL as only the first packet of a flow had to be evaluated by the ACL.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] As a switching technology, NetFlow was replaced around 1995 by Cisco Express Forwarding.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] This first appeared on Cisco 12000 routers, and later replaced NetFlow switching on advanced IOS for the Cisco 7200 and Cisco 7500.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] As of 2012, technologies similar to NetFlow switching are still in use in most firewalls and software-based IP routers.
[src:netflow-sflow/netflow] For instance the conntrack feature of the Netfilter framework used by Linux.
[src:netflow-sflow/network-management] A number of applications and protocols exist to support network and network device management.
[src:netflow-sflow/network-management] Network management allows IT professionals to monitor network components within a large network area.
[src:netflow-sflow/network-management] Access methods include the SNMP, command-line interface (CLI), custom XML, CMIP, Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI), Transaction Language 1 (TL1), CORBA, NETCONF, RESTCONF and the Java Management Extensions (JMX).
[src:netflow-sflow/network-management] Schemas include the Structure of Management Information (SMI), YANG, WBEM, the Common Information Model (CIM Schema), and MTOSI amongst others.
[src:netflow-sflow/network-management] Effective network management can provide positive strategic impacts.
[src:netflow-sflow/network-management] For example, in the case of developing an infrastructure, providing participants with some interactive space allows them to collaborate with each other, thereby promoting overall benefits.
[src:netflow-sflow/network-management] At the same time, the value of network management to the strategic network is also affected by the relationship between participants.
[src:netflow-sflow/network-management] Active participation, interaction and collaboration can make them more trusting of each other and enhance cohesion.
[src:netflow-sflow/network-traffic-control] In computer networking, **network traffic control** is the process of managing, controlling or reducing the network traffic, particularly Internet bandwidth, e.g. by the network scheduler.
[src:netflow-sflow/network-traffic-control] It is used by network administrators, to reduce congestion, latency and packet loss.
[src:netflow-sflow/network-traffic-control] In order to use these tools effectively, it is necessary to measure the network traffic to determine the causes of network congestion and attack those problems specifically.
[src:netflow-sflow/network-traffic-control] Network traffic control is an important subject in datacenters as it is necessary for efficient use of datacenter network bandwidth and for maintaining service level agreements.
[src:netflow-sflow/network-traffic-control] Traffic shaping is the retiming (delaying) of packets (or frames) until they meet specified bandwidth and or burstiness limits.
[src:netflow-sflow/network-traffic-control] Since such delays involve queues that are nearly always finite and, once full, excess traffic is nearly always dropped (discarded), traffic shaping nearly always implies traffic policing as well.
[src:netflow-sflow/network-traffic-control] Traffic policing is the dropping (discarding) or reduction in priority (demoting) of packets (or frames) that exceed some specified bandwidth and or burstiness limit.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Although the term commonly refers to wireless data transfer mechanisms (e.g., using radio, ultrasonic, or infrared systems), it also encompasses data transferred over other media such as a telephone or computer network, optical link or other wired communications like power line carriers.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Many modern telemetry systems take advantage of the low cost and ubiquity of GSM networks by using SMS to receive and transmit telemetry data.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] A *telemeter* is a physical device used in telemetry.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] It consists of a sensor, a transmission path, and a display, recording, or control device.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Electronic devices are widely used in telemetry and can be wireless or hard-wired, analog or digital.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Other technologies are also possible, such as mechanical, hydraulic and optical.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry may be commutated to allow the transmission of multiple data streams in a fixed frame.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] The beginning of industrial telemetry lies in the steam age, although the sensor was not called *telemeter* at that time.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Examples are James Watt's (1736-1819) additions to his steam engines for monitoring from a (near) distance such as the mercury pressure gauge and the fly-ball governor.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In 1889 this led an author in the Institution of Civil Engineers proceedings to suggest that the term for the rangefinder telemeter might be replaced with tacheometer.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In the 1930s use of electrical telemeters grew rapidly.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] The electrical strain gauge was widely used in rocket and aviation research and the radiosonde was invented for meteorological measurements.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] The advent of World War II gave an impetus to industrial development and henceforth many of these telemeters became commercially viable.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Carrying on from rocket research, radio telemetry was used routinely as space exploration got underway.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Spacecraft are in a place where a physical connection is not possible, leaving radio or other electromagnetic waves (such as infrared lasers) as the only viable option for telemetry.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] During crewed space missions it is used to monitor not only parameters of the vehicle, but also the health and life support of the astronauts.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] During the Cold War telemetry found uses in espionage.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] US intelligence found that they could monitor the telemetry from Soviet missile tests by building a telemeter of their own to intercept the radio signals and hence learn a great deal about Soviet capabilities.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemeters are the physical devices used in telemetry.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetering information over wire had its origins in the 19th century.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] One of the first data-transmission circuits was developed in 1845 between the Russian Tsar's Winter Palace and army headquarters.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In 1874, French engineers built a system of weather and snow-depth sensors on Mont Blanc that transmitted real-time information to Paris.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Michalke patented the selsyn, a circuit for sending synchronized rotation information over a distance.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In 1906 a set of seismic stations were built with telemetering to the Pulkovo Observatory in Russia.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In 1912, Commonwealth Edison developed a system of telemetry to monitor electrical loads on its power grid.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] The Panama Canal (completed 1913–1914) used extensive telemetry systems to monitor locks and water levels.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Wireless telemetry made early appearances in the radiosonde, developed concurrently in 1930 by Robert Bureau in France and Pavel Molchanov in Russia.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Molchanov's system modulated temperature and pressure measurements by converting them to wireless Morse code.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] The German V-2 rocket used a system of primitive multiplexed radio signals called "Messina" to report four rocket parameters, but it was so unreliable that Wernher von Braun once claimed it was more useful to watch the rocket through binoculars.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In the US and the USSR, the Messina system was quickly replaced with better systems; in both cases, based on pulse-position modulation (PPM).
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Early Soviet missile and space telemetry systems which were developed in the late 1940s used either PPM (e.g., the Tral telemetry system developed by OKB-MEI) or pulse-duration modulation (e.g., the RTS-5 system developed by NII-885).
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In the United States, early work employed similar systems, but were later replaced by pulse-code modulation (PCM) (for example, in the Mars probe Mariner 4).
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Later Soviet interplanetary probes used redundant radio systems, transmitting telemetry by PCM on a decimeter band and PPM on a centimeter band.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Although the two terms are closely related, telemetry and telematics are used differently depending on the field.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telematics, by contrast, emerged later as a broader, more applied concept that combines telemetry with telecommunications, informatics, and digital fleet platforms.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In short, telemetry is the enabling technology (remote measurement and data transmission), while telematics describes the integrated, digitalized applications that build on telemetry to deliver business, safety, and operational insights.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Weather balloons use telemetry to transmit meteorological data since 1920.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry is used to transmit drilling mechanics and formation evaluation information uphole, in real time, as a well is drilled.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] These services are known as Measurement while drilling and Logging while drilling.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Information acquired thousands of feet below ground, while drilling, is sent through the drilling hole to the surface sensors and the demodulation software.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] The pressure wave (sana) is translated into useful information after DSP and noise filters.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] This information is used for Formation evaluation, Drilling Optimization, and Geosteering.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry is used in modern motor racing, allowing race engineers to interpret data collected during a test or race and use it to properly tune the car for optimum performance.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Systems used in series such as Formula One have become advanced to the point where the potential lap time of the car can be calculated, and this time is what the driver is expected to meet.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Examples of measurements on a race car include accelerations (G forces) in three axes, temperature readings, wheel speed, and suspension displacement.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In Formula One, driver input is also recorded so the team can assess driver performance and (in case of an accident) the FIA can determine or rule out driver error as a possible cause.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Later developments include two-way telemetry which allows engineers to update calibrations on the car in real time (even while it is out on the track).
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In Formula One, two-way telemetry surfaced in the early 1990s and consisted of a message display on the dashboard which the team could update.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Its development continued until May 2001, when it was first allowed on the cars.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] By 2002, teams were able to change engine mapping and deactivate engine sensors from the pit while the car was on the track.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] For the 2003 season, the FIA banned two-way telemetry from Formula One; however, the technology may be used in other types of racing or on road cars.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] One way telemetry system has also been applied in R/C racing car to get information by car's sensors like: engine RPM, voltage, temperatures, throttle.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In the transportation industry, a Fleet telematics system is used to provide information about a vehicle or driver's performance by collecting data from on-board sensors, such as a GPS tracking unit or a telematics control unit (TCU).
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] This is undertaken for various reasons ranging from staff compliance monitoring, insurance rating, fuel management to predictive maintenance.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] As part of an Intelligent transportation system, telemetry is used to link traffic counter devices to data recorders to measure traffic flows and vehicle lengths and weights.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry is used by the railway industry for measuring the health of trackage.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] This permits optimized and focused predictive and preventative maintenance.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Typically this is done with specialized trains, such as the New Measurement Train used in the United Kingdom by Network Rail, which can check for track defects, such as problems with gauge, and deformations in the rail.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Japan uses similar, but quicker trains, nicknamed Doctor Yellow.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Such trains, besides checking the tracks, can also verify whether or not there are any problems with the overhead power supply (catenary), where it is installed.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Dedicated rail inspection companies, such as Sperry Rail, have their own customized rail cars and rail-wheel equipped trucks, that use a variety of methods, including lasers, ultrasound, and induction (measuring resulting magnetic fields from running electricity into rails) to find any defects.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Most activities related to healthy crops and good yields depend on timely availability of weather and soil data.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Therefore, wireless weather stations play a major role in disease prevention and precision irrigation.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Because local micro-climates can vary significantly, such data needs to come from within the crop.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Monitoring stations usually transmit data back by terrestrial radio, although occasionally satellite systems are used.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Solar power is often employed to make the station independent of the power grid.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry is used in water management, including water quality and stream gauging functions.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Major applications include AMR (automatic meter reading), groundwater monitoring, leak detection in distribution pipelines and equipment surveillance.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Having data available in almost real time allows quick reactions to events in the field.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry control allows engineers to intervene with assets such as pumps and by remotely switching pumps on or off depending on the circumstances.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry is used in complex systems such as missiles, RPVs, spacecraft, oil rigs, and chemical plants since it allows the automatic monitoring, alerting, and record-keeping necessary for efficient and safe operation.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Space agencies such as NASA, ISRO, the European Space Agency (ESA), and other agencies use telemetry and/or telecommand systems to collect data from spacecraft and satellites.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry is used in the development of missiles, satellites and aircraft because the system might be destroyed during or after the test.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Engineers need critical system parameters to analyze (and improve) the performance of the system.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In the absence of telemetry, this data would often be unavailable.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry is used by crewed or uncrewed spacecraft for data transmission.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Distances of more than 25.1 billion kilometers (May 2025) have been covered, e.g., by Voyager 1.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In rocketry, telemetry equipment forms an integral part of the rocket range assets used to monitor the position and health of a launch vehicle to determine range safety flight termination criteria (Range purpose is for public safety).
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Problems include the extreme environment (temperature, acceleration and vibration), the energy supply, antenna alignment and (at long distances, e.g., in spaceflight) signal travel time.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Today nearly every type of aircraft, missiles, or spacecraft carries a wireless telemetry system as it is tested.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Aeronautical mobile telemetry is used for the safety of the pilots and persons on the ground during flight tests.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry from an on-board flight test instrumentation system is the primary source of real-time measurement and status information transmitted during the testing of crewed and uncrewed aircraft.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Intercepted telemetry was an important source of intelligence for the United States and UK when Soviet missiles were tested; for this purpose, the United States operated a listening post in Iran.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Eventually, the Russians discovered the United States intelligence-gathering network and encrypted their missile-test telemetry signals.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry was also a source for the Soviets, who operated listening ships in Cardigan Bay to eavesdrop on UK missile tests performed in the area.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In factories, buildings and houses, energy consumption of systems such as HVAC are monitored at multiple locations; related parameters (e.g., temperature) are sent via wireless telemetry to a central location.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] The information is collected and processed, enabling the most efficient use of energy.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Such systems also facilitate predictive maintenance.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Many resources need to be distributed over wide areas.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry is useful in these cases, since it allows the logistics system to channel resources where they are needed, as well as provide security for those assets; principal examples of this are dry goods, fluids, and granular bulk solids.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] This facilitates knowledge of their location, and can record their status and disposition, as when merchandise with barcode labels is scanned through a checkout reader at point-of-sale systems in a retail store.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Stationary or hand-held barcode RFID scanners or Optical reader with remote communications, can be used to expedite inventory tracking and counting in stores, warehouses, shipping terminals, transportation carriers and factories.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Fluids stored in tanks are a principal object of constant commercial telemetry.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry is used to communicate the variable measurements of flow and tank level sensors detecting fluid movements and/or volumes by pneumatic, hydrostatic, or differential pressure; tank-confined ultrasonic, radar or Doppler effect echoes; or mechanical or magnetic sensors.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry of bulk solids is common for tracking and reporting the volume status and condition of grain and livestock feed bins, powdered or granular food, powders and pellets for manufacturing, sand and gravel, and other granular bulk solids.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] While technology associated with fluid tank monitoring also applies, in part, to granular bulk solids, reporting of overall container weight, or other gross characteristics and conditions, are sometimes required, owing to bulk solids' more complex and variable physical characteristics.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry is used for patients (biotelemetry) who are at risk of abnormal heart activity, generally in a coronary care unit.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry specialists are sometimes used to monitor many patients within a hospital.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Such patients are outfitted with measuring, recording and transmitting devices.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] A data log can be useful in diagnosis of the patient's condition by doctors.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] An alerting function can alert nurses if the patient is suffering from an acute (or dangerous) condition.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Systems are available in medical-surgical nursing for monitoring to rule out a heart condition, or to monitor a response to antiarrhythmic medications such as amiodarone.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] A new and emerging application for telemetry is in the field of neurophysiology, or neurotelemetry.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Neurophysiology is the study of the central and peripheral nervous systems through the recording of bioelectrical activity, whether spontaneous or stimulated.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In neurotelemetry (NT) the electroencephalogram (EEG) of a patient is monitored remotely by a registered EEG technologist using advanced communication software.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] The goal of neurotelemetry is to recognize a decline in a patient's condition before physical signs and symptoms are present.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Neurotelemetry is synonymous with real-time continuous video EEG monitoring and has application in the epilepsy monitoring unit, neuro ICU, pediatric ICU and newborn ICU.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Due to the labor-intensive nature of continuous EEG monitoring NT is typically done in the larger academic teaching hospitals using in-house programs that include R.EEG Technologists, IT support staff, neurologist and neurophysiologist and monitoring support personnel.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Modern microprocessor speeds, software algorithms and video data compression allow hospitals to centrally record and monitor continuous digital EEGs of multiple critically ill patients simultaneously.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Neurotelemetry and continuous EEG monitoring provides dynamic information about brain function that permits early detection of changes in neurologic status, which is especially useful when the clinical examination is limited.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry is used to study wildlife, and has been useful for monitoring threatened species at the individual level.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Animals under study can be outfitted with instrumentation tags, which include sensors that measure temperature, diving depth and duration (for marine animals), speed and location (using GPS or Argos packages).
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry tags can give researchers information about animal behavior, functions, and their environment.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] This information is then either stored (with archival tags) or the tags can send (or transmit) their information to a satellite or handheld receiving device.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Capturing and marking wild animals can put them at some risk, so it is important to minimize these impacts.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] At a 2005 workshop in Las Vegas, a seminar noted the introduction of telemetry equipment which would allow vending machines to communicate sales and inventory data to a route truck or to a headquarters.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] This data could be used for a variety of purposes, such as eliminating the need for drivers to make a first trip to see which items needed to be restocked before delivering the inventory.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Retailers also use RFID tags to track inventory and prevent shoplifting.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Most of these tags passively respond to RFID readers (e.g., at the cashier), but active RFID tags are available which periodically transmit location information to a base station.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] A telemetry-based Tracking system is useful for tracking persons and property in law enforcement.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] An ankle collar worn by convicts on probation can warn authorities if a person violates the terms of his or her parole, such as by straying from authorized boundaries or visiting an unauthorized location.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry has also enabled bait cars, where law enforcement can rig a car with cameras and tracking equipment and leave it somewhere they expect it to be stolen.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] When stolen the telemetry equipment reports the location of the vehicle, enabling a Stolen vehicle recovery process where law enforcement can deactivate the engine and lock the doors when it is stopped by responding officers.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In some countries, telemetry is used to measure the amount of electrical energy consumed.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] The electricity meter communicates with a concentrator, and the latter sends the information through GPRS or GSM to the energy provider's server.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry is also used for the remote monitoring of substations and their equipment.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] For data transmission, phase line carrier systems operating on frequencies between 30 and 400 kHz are sometimes used.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In falconry, "telemetry" means a small radio transmitter carried by a bird of prey that will allow the bird's owner to track it when it is out of sight.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry is used in testing hostile environments which are dangerous to humans.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Examples include munitions storage facilities, radioactive sites, volcanoes, deep sea, and outer space.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Telemetry is used in many battery operated wireless systems to inform monitoring personnel when the battery power is reaching a low point and the end item needs fresh batteries.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In the mining industry, telemetry serves two main purposes: the measurement of key parameters from mining equipment and the monitoring of safety practices.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] The information provided by the collection and analysis of key parameters allows for root-cause identification of inefficient operations, unsafe practices and incorrect equipment usage for maximizing productivity and safety.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Further applications of the technology allow for sharing knowledge and best practices across the organization.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In software, telemetry is used to gather data on the use and performance of applications and application components, e.g. how often certain features are used, measurements of start-up time and processing time, hardware, application crashes, and general usage statistics and/or user behavior.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] In some cases, very detailed data is reported like individual window metrics, counts of used features, and individual function timings.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] This kind of telemetry can be useful to software developers to receive data from a wide variety of endpoints that can't possibly all be tested in-house, as well as getting data on the popularity of certain features and whether they should be given priority or be considered for removal.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] Due to concerns about privacy since software telemetry can easily be used to profile users, telemetry in user software is often user choice, commonly presented as an opt-out feature (requiring explicit user action to disable it) or user choice during the software installation process.
[src:netflow-sflow/telemetry] As in other telecommunications fields, international standards exist for telemetry equipment and software.
